      dek: `The synopsis sells the film; the director's statement sells the filmmaker. It's where press find their human angle, and where you turn "another indie" into "a film with a story behind it." This chapter covers the statement, plus the bios and credits that make your kit look complete and professional.`,
      body: `<p>A synopsis tells people what the film is about; the <strong>director's statement</strong> tells them why it exists and why they should care about the person who made it. It's a short, personal piece — usually a paragraph or two — in your own voice, explaining what drew you to this story, what you were trying to say or capture, and what the film means to you. Press love it because it hands them the human angle they need to write a story: not just "a film about X," but "a filmmaker who made a film about X because of Y." Programmers read it to understand your intent and sensibility. And it's often the most memorable thing in an EPK, because it's the one part with a beating heart. Filmmakers frequently skip it or fill it with vague, grandiose statements about "the human condition," which is a wasted opportunity — a genuine, specific, honest statement is a powerful asset. Alongside it, this chapter covers the two workmanlike pieces that make a kit look complete: bios and credits.</p>

<h2>Writing the statement, bios, and credits</h2>

<p>How to handle each:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Director's statement — be specific and personal.</b> Say what actually drew you to this story, in your own voice. A concrete detail ("I grew up in a town like this one") beats abstract grandeur. Honest and particular is memorable; vague and lofty is forgettable.</li>
  <li><b>Keep it short and genuine.</b> A paragraph or two, not an essay. Avoid clichés and self-importance. Write like you're telling a friend why this film mattered enough to make — that tone lands.</li>
  <li><b>Give press an angle.</b> Ask what's unusual or human about your journey with the film — a personal connection, an obstacle, a reason it had to be made — and put it in the statement. That's what becomes the story.</li>
  <li><b>Cast &amp; crew bios — short and professional.</b> A few sentences each for key people: notable credits, relevant background, one line of personality. Keep lengths consistent and tone professional. Grab headshots to accompany them.</li>
  <li><b>The credits block (billing block).</b> The formal list of who did what, in correct industry order. Get names spelled right and roles accurate — errors here are glaring and, for some contracts, contractually required to be exact.</li>
  <li><b>Accuracy is everything.</b> Double-check every name, title, and credit. A misspelled cast name or wrong role in your EPK is unprofessional and can genuinely upset the people who trusted you with their work.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The human angle is your edge</h2>

<p>The reason the director's statement deserves real care is that <strong>for an indie film, the story of how and why it was made is often as compelling to press as the film itself</strong> — and it's an angle only you can provide. A journalist covering hundreds of films is looking for a hook, a reason this one is worth a paragraph, and your statement can hand it to them: the personal stakes, the against-the-odds production, the question that obsessed you. So resist the urge to be impressively vague and instead be specifically honest, because specificity is what makes writing memorable and generality is what makes it disappear. The bios and credits, meanwhile, are less about persuasion and more about <em>signaling professionalism and getting it right</em>: a clean, consistent bio section and an accurate credits block tell everyone you take the work — and your collaborators — seriously, while typos and missing credits do the opposite and can strain relationships with the people who helped you. A practical workflow: write your statement, then draft short bios for your principals, then assemble the credits block carefully from your actual production paperwork (not from memory), and have someone check every name. Keep the statement and bios in a couple of lengths so you can trim to fit different outlets. And revisit the statement as your perspective on the film evolves — the way you understand your own film often deepens after it meets an audience, and a statement written with that hindsight can be even stronger. Together, the statement gives your EPK a soul and the bios and credits give it credibility. With the written pieces in hand, the next chapter turns to the images that carry as much weight as any words: your stills, poster, and key art.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A synopsis sells the film; the director's statement sells the filmmaker. For an indie, the story of why it was made is often as compelling to press as the film — and only you can give them that angle.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first director's statement was three sentences of pure fog about "exploring truth and the human spirit" — meaningless, and every journalist ignored it. For the next film I wrote the real reason I'd made it: a specific, personal thing I almost felt too exposed to admit. That paragraph became the hook for nearly every piece of press we got — reviewers quoted it, interviewers asked about it. The honest, specific statement did more for coverage than the polished synopsis. And a separate hard lesson: I once shipped an EPK with a lead actor's name misspelled. They noticed. Check every name. The statement gives your kit heart; accurate credits keep your relationships intact.</p>
</div>`,
