      seoDesc: "How to write a film press release — the news-style announcement journalists can run almost as-is, with the right structure, headline, and quote. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 8 of Building Your EPK.",
      dek: `A press release is a favor to a busy journalist: a ready-to-run, news-style announcement they can turn into coverage with almost no work. Written well, it practically writes the article for them. Here's the structure and the small conventions that make yours look like it came from a real publicist.`,
      body: `<p>A press release is a specific kind of document with a specific purpose: it's a short, formal announcement, written in a neutral news style, that gives journalists a story they can publish almost as-is. It exists because reporters and bloggers are flooded and time-poor, and they gravitate toward the stories that are easiest to run. If you hand them a well-structured release — a clear news hook, the key facts up front, a usable quote, and everything they need to write a piece — you've dramatically raised the odds they'll cover you, because you've removed the work. The key mental shift is that a press release is <strong>not an ad and not your synopsis</strong>; it's written like a news article a journalist could lightly edit and run under their own byline. It has a real hook (a premiere, a release date, an award, a festival selection), it leads with the most important information, and it stays factual and quotable rather than salesy. Let me give you the structure.</p>

<h2>The anatomy of a film press release</h2>

<p>A standard release, top to bottom:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>"FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE" &amp; date.</b> The conventional header at the top, with the release date. A small formality that signals you know the format.</li>
  <li><b>Headline.</b> A clear, news-style title announcing the actual news — the premiere, the award, the release. Make it factual and compelling, not a marketing slogan.</li>
  <li><b>The lead paragraph.</b> The most important paragraph — who, what, when, where, why, in the first sentences. A journalist should grasp the whole story from this alone. Put the news first.</li>
  <li><b>Body paragraphs.</b> Supporting detail in descending order of importance (the "inverted pyramid"): the film's premise, key names, festival/context, so an editor can cut from the bottom without losing the point.</li>
  <li><b>A quote.</b> A short, usable quote from you (the director) or a producer — something a journalist can drop straight into their article. Make it genuine and printable, not corporate fluff.</li>
  <li><b>Boilerplate &amp; contact.</b> A brief standard "about the film/production" paragraph, then clear press contact info (name, email). End with "###" or "-30-", the traditional close.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Write it like news, and tailor it</h2>

<p>The craft that makes a press release actually get used comes down to a few disciplines. First, <strong>lead with the news, not the setup.</strong> The single most common amateur mistake is burying the announcement under paragraphs of atmosphere or backstory; a journalist should know the who/what/when in the first two sentences, because that's how news is written and how editors scan. Second, <strong>keep it to one page and stay factual.</strong> Releases are short and neutral in tone — the film "premieres" and "was selected," not "is a breathtaking triumph." Save the enthusiasm for the quote, which is the one place a subjective, human voice belongs (and where journalists expect to find a printable line). Third, <strong>give them a genuine hook.</strong> "We made a film" is not news; "This film premieres at [event] on [date]" or "won [award]" is. Anchor the release to a real, timely event, which is exactly why a press release gets swapped or rewritten per occasion — you'll have a premiere release, an award release, a release-date release, each hung on its own hook. Fourth, <strong>tailor when it matters.</strong> A generic release blasted to everyone underperforms a version lightly customized to the outlet or the specific angle; even small tailoring signals you're a real person, not a spam cannon. And fifth, <strong>make the quote count</strong> — a vivid, specific line from the director gives the piece its human center and is often the sentence that survives into the final article. A practical note echoing earlier chapters: your press release is one document <em>inside</em> your EPK, and the reader will want the rest (stills, synopsis, contact) right there too, so a release usually travels alongside — or links to — the full kit. Write your first release now around your most likely first hook (your premiere or festival debut), keep it as a template you adapt for future news, and you'll be ready to feed the press exactly what they need, when they need it. With every written and visual piece now in hand, Module 3 turns to assembly and use — starting with building the actual EPK document.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A press release is a favor to a busy journalist — a story they can run with almost no work. Lead with the news, keep it factual and one page, and put your one printable, human line in the quote.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first press release opened with three flowery paragraphs about the "journey" of making the film, and buried the actual news — our festival premiere and date — near the bottom. No one ran it; editors don't dig. I rewrote it the news way: headline stating the premiere, lead paragraph with who/what/when/where, then detail, then a real quote from me, then contact info. Same film, and this time outlets picked it up almost verbatim. The lesson stuck: a press release isn't your voice being poetic, it's news being handed over ready to print. Lead with the story, keep it tight, and give them one good quote — the rest is format.</p>
</div>`,
