      dek: `You've got all the pieces — now you assemble them into the thing itself. This chapter is about laying out a clean, well-ordered, professional-looking EPK document (usually a PDF) that presents your materials so they read as polished, not thrown together. Same content, night-and-day impression.`,
      body: `<p>Now comes the assembly. You have your logline, synopsis, director's statement, bios, credits, stills, poster, press release, and details — this chapter is about arranging them into a single, cohesive, professional document, almost always a <strong>PDF</strong>, that someone can open and immediately grasp. Here's the truth that makes this chapter matter: <strong>the exact same materials can read as "professional film" or "amateur project" depending entirely on how they're laid out.</strong> A clean design with a logical order, consistent fonts, and breathing room signals competence; a wall of mismatched text, random image sizes, and no structure signals the opposite — even if every word is identical. You don't need to be a graphic designer to make a good EPK, but you do need to respect a few layout basics and follow a sensible order. The goal is a document that looks like it came from someone who knows what they're doing, because that perception carries over to how people judge the film.</p>

<h2>Laying out the EPK</h2>

<p>How to structure and design the document:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Open with the key art.</b> Lead with your poster or a striking still and the title — a strong cover page. First impressions count, and this is the first page they see.</li>
  <li><b>Logical order.</b> A natural flow: cover, logline/short synopsis, film details/fact sheet, longer synopsis, director's statement, cast &amp; crew bios, stills, press release, reviews/laurels, and contact info. Front-load the essentials.</li>
  <li><b>Consistent, clean design.</b> One or two fonts, consistent headings, generous white space, aligned elements. Restraint reads as professional; clutter and clashing fonts read as amateur.</li>
  <li><b>Let images breathe.</b> Present stills at a good size, well-placed, not crammed or stretched. Your poster and photos are strengths — give them room to work.</li>
  <li><b>Keep it reasonable length.</b> Complete but not bloated — enough to cover everything, tight enough to respect the reader's time. Every page should earn its place.</li>
  <li><b>Export a clean PDF.</b> PDF preserves your layout everywhere and is the expected format. Keep the file size sensible (compress images enough to email, high enough quality to look good), and name it clearly, e.g. "FilmTitle_EPK.pdf".</li>
</ul>

<h2>Tools, templates, and getting it done</h2>

<p>You might worry you can't design this yourself — you can, and you have options at every skill level. If you're comfortable with design tools, a layout app gives you full control; if you're not, <strong>a template is your friend</strong> — plenty of free and low-cost EPK/press-kit templates exist that you drop your content into and export, and even a well-used word processor or slide tool can produce a clean PDF if you keep the design simple and consistent. The point isn't fancy design; it's <em>tidy, legible, organized</em> design, which is completely achievable without a designer. That said, if visual polish genuinely isn't your thing and this is an important film, a few dollars or a favor to a designer for a nice template or a one-time layout is money well spent, because the document's look shapes the film's perception. A few practical disciplines that separate a pro EPK from a rough one: proofread everything one more time in the final layout (typos hide until they're in a nice document), check that every image is high enough resolution to not look pixelated at print size, make sure your contact info is unmissable, and view the finished PDF on a phone as well as a computer, since people will open it on both. Keep the master editable so you can update it — because remember from earlier, an EPK is a living document, and you'll be swapping in new laurels, quotes, and posters over the film's life. One more tip: build it modularly, so the pieces (a stills-only PDF, the press release alone, a one-sheet) can be pulled out and sent individually when someone asks for just one thing. When you're done, you'll have a single, polished document that represents your film professionally and answers most requests with one attachment or link — a genuinely powerful asset. But a PDF isn't the only form your EPK should take; the next chapter covers the digital, web-based version that's increasingly what people expect and that never lands in a spam folder.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The exact same materials read as "professional film" or "amateur project" depending entirely on the layout. You don't need to be a designer — just tidy, legible, and organized — but the document's look becomes the film's reputation.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I once had a great set of materials — strong synopsis, good stills, a real poster — pasted into a single Word doc with three different fonts, images at random sizes, and no structure. It looked like a ransom note. A friend dropped the identical content into a simple two-font template with a poster cover page and consistent headings, exported a clean PDF, and it suddenly looked like it came from a distributor. Same words, same photos — the layout was the entire difference. Now I never send raw materials; I always assemble a tidy PDF, proof it in the final layout, and check it on my phone. Presentation is content when it comes to an EPK.</p>
</div>`,
