      dek: `A PDF is great, but a web-based EPK is often better: a single link you can share anywhere, that's always up to date, never bounces from a spam filter, and lets press download exactly what they need. This chapter is about building the online version of your press kit.`,
      body: `<p>A downloadable PDF is a solid EPK, but the modern expectation — and often the better tool — is a <strong>digital, web-based press kit</strong>: a page (or a section of your film's website) that holds all your materials and lives at a single link. The advantages are real and add up fast. A link is easy to share and never gets caught in a spam filter or bounced for being too large the way a big PDF attachment can. It's always current — when you win a laurel or land a review, you update the page once and everyone who has the link sees the latest version, with no re-sending. It lets press download exactly what they want (all the stills, or just one; the poster; the press release) instead of forcing a giant download. And it looks modern and professional, which quietly reinforces that you know what you're doing. So the ideal setup is often <em>both</em>: a polished PDF for those who want a document, and a web press page for those who prefer a link — with the page also offering the PDF as a download.</p>

<h2>What a good digital press page includes</h2>

<p>Your online EPK should offer:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Everything from your PDF, laid out for the web.</b> Logline, synopsis, director's statement, bios, credits, film details — as readable web content, not just an embedded document.</li>
  <li><b>Downloadable assets.</b> High-res stills (individually and as a zip), the poster in usable formats, and the press release and full EPK as downloadable files. Make grabbing what they need one click.</li>
  <li><b>The trailer, embedded.</b> A watchable trailer right on the page (embedded from your video host), plus a link. Press want to see it without hunting.</li>
  <li><b>Clear, unmissable contact info.</b> Press/booking contact prominently placed — the whole point is to make reaching you effortless.</li>
  <li><b>A clean, on-brand look.</b> Consistent with your poster and film's tone, mobile-friendly, and simple to navigate. It's a reflection of the film, so keep it tidy.</li>
  <li><b>A short, shareable URL.</b> A memorable link (your film's site /press, or a dedicated page) you can drop into emails, submission forms, and your socials.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to build it without a budget — and use it well</h2>

<p>You do not need to be a web developer or spend much to have a professional digital EPK, and there are a few routes depending on what you already have. If your film has a website (the next stage of your marketing, and its own topic), the simplest path is a <strong>"Press" page on that site</strong> holding all your materials and downloads — one page, done. If you don't have a site, there are dedicated press-kit link tools and simple site builders that let you assemble a clean press page and share it as a link with little or no cost, and even a basic free website or a well-organized shared cloud folder (with everything clearly labeled and downloadable) can serve in a pinch — though a real page always looks more professional than a raw folder. The key qualities are the same regardless of tool: everything in one place, easy to download, mobile-friendly, current, and reachable at a shareable link. Two disciplines make the digital EPK pay off. First, <strong>keep it updated</strong> — this is the digital version's superpower, so actually use it: add each new laurel, quote, and review the moment it happens, so the link you've already sent to a hundred people always shows your latest. Second, <strong>lead with the link in your outreach</strong> — when you email a journalist or fill a submission form, give them the press-page URL (with the PDF available there too), because a link that opens instantly beats an attachment they have to download, and it won't trip a spam filter. A practical safety note: keep the underlying files backed up and organized regardless of where the page lives, so if a hosting tool changes or disappears, you can rebuild fast. With a strong digital EPK plus your PDF, you can answer virtually any press request with a single link, instantly and professionally. The next chapter narrows in on one specific, high-stakes use of all this — the festival press kit, where the requirements are particular and the deadlines are strict.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A web-based EPK is a single link that never hits a spam filter, always shows your latest laurels, and lets press download exactly what they need. Build both a PDF and a press page — then lead every pitch with the link.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I used to email a 40-MB EPK PDF to press and half the time it bounced or vanished into spam. Then I made a simple "Press" page on the film's site — all the materials, the trailer embedded, stills as a downloadable zip, the PDF available too, one clean URL. Suddenly outreach got easier: I'd just paste the link, it opened instantly on any device, and when we won a festival I added the laurel once and every journalist who had the link saw it. The web EPK didn't just look more professional — it removed all the friction. Now the link is the first thing in every pitch, and the PDF is just a download on the page for anyone who wants it.</p>
</div>`,
