      seoTitle: "The Festival Press Kit: Film Festival Press Kit | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "Film festival press kit — what festivals specifically require, how it differs from a general EPK, and how to deliver it on their deadline. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 11 of Building Your EPK.",
      dek: `Festivals are where most indie films meet their first press, and they have specific requirements and hard deadlines. Your EPK is the foundation, but the festival version needs particular pieces delivered in a particular way, on time. Here's how to nail the festival press kit.`,
      body: `<p>For most indie films, a festival is the first real public moment — the premiere, the first reviews, the first audience — and festivals run on materials. When you're accepted, the festival needs press materials from you to build their program, their website, and their press outreach, and the journalists covering the festival will draw on those materials to decide what to write about and how. So the festival press kit is your general EPK put to its first serious use, and getting it right can meaningfully affect how much attention your film gets in the crowded festival environment. The good news is that if you've built a strong EPK from the earlier chapters, you already have the foundation; the festival version is mostly about <strong>delivering the right pieces, in the festival's required format, by the festival's deadline</strong> — plus a couple of festival-specific touches. Let me cover what's particular about it.</p>

<h2>What the festival press kit needs</h2>

<p>Beyond your standard EPK, festivals care about:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Exactly what they ask for.</b> Festivals send delivery requirements: specific fields (synopsis lengths, credits format), image specs, deadlines. Read them carefully and provide precisely what's requested — not more, not less, in their format.</li>
  <li><b>Program-ready copy.</b> They need a synopsis that fits their program (often a specific word count) and correct, complete credits. Have short and long versions ready so you can supply the right length instantly.</li>
  <li><b>High-res stills to spec.</b> Festivals publish your stills in programs and press. Provide print-quality images at the dimensions/format they specify, named and captioned clearly.</li>
  <li><b>Your poster / key art.</b> For their program grid, website, and screening slides. Supply the formats they ask for, legible at small sizes.</li>
  <li><b>Festival laurels.</b> Once selected, you'll receive the festival's official laurel — add it to your poster and EPK. Laurels are social proof that compound as your film travels the circuit.</li>
  <li><b>A festival-specific press release.</b> Announce your selection/premiere with a release tailored to that festival and date — great outreach fuel and exactly the kind of hook press respond to.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Deadlines, professionalism, and the circuit</h2>

<p>Two realities make or break the festival press kit, and both echo the delivery mindset from across this project. First, <strong>the deadline is real and firm.</strong> Festival delivery dates for materials are fixed, staff are juggling hundreds of films, and a late or incomplete submission at best creates a scramble and at worst means your film gets less or worse promotion because your materials weren't ready when they built the program. The filmmakers who get treated well are the ones who respond fast and deliver complete, correct materials on time — so when the acceptance comes, read the requirements immediately and deliver early. This is dramatically easier if your EPK is already built (which is the whole point of doing it in advance): an acceptance becomes a matter of pulling the requested pieces and formatting them, not a from-scratch panic. Second, <strong>festivals are a circuit, and your kit compounds.</strong> As your film plays more festivals, it accumulates laurels, reviews, and audience response, and your press kit should grow with it — each new laurel added to the poster, each good review added as a pull-quote — so that by your fifth festival your kit is far stronger than at your first, and that momentum helps attract press and buyers. So treat the festival press kit not as a one-off but as a living asset that levels up across the circuit. A few practical habits: keep a simple record of each festival's specific requirements and deadlines (especially if you're in several at once, so you don't send the wrong thing to the wrong place), be responsive and gracious with festival staff and press (relationships in this world matter and travel), and after each festival, harvest what you gained — laurels, quotes, contacts — back into your master EPK. Do this and each festival makes your film more visible and your kit more powerful. Handle festivals well and they launch your film into the world; handle the materials poorly and a hard-won selection gets less than it deserved. With your festival kit sorted, the final chapter pulls back to the biggest question: how you actually use all of this to land press and get your film seen.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Your EPK is the foundation; the festival version is about delivering the right pieces, in the right format, by the deadline. And festivals are a circuit — your kit compounds, gaining a laurel and a quote at every stop.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>At my first festival I delivered materials late and half-formatted, and it showed — my film got the bare minimum in the program while filmmakers who'd delivered clean, complete kits on time got features and better placement. Painful, and entirely my fault. Now, the moment an acceptance lands, I open the delivery requirements, pull the exact pieces from my ready EPK, and send them early and complete. And I treat the kit as a growing thing: every laurel goes on the poster, every good review becomes a quote. By the time a film has played a few festivals, its press kit is a genuine asset — and that momentum is what gets the attention of the outlets and buyers who matter.</p>
</div>`,
