      dek: `A perfect EPK sitting on your hard drive does nothing. This final chapter is about putting it to work — pitching the right journalists, giving them a reason to care, and turning your press kit into actual coverage that gets your film seen. The EPK is the tool; this is how you use it.`,
      body: `<p>Everything you've built across this course exists for one purpose: to help your film get seen, and the most direct way it does that is by making press coverage possible. But an EPK is a <em>tool</em>, and a tool only works when you use it. Plenty of filmmakers build a beautiful press kit and then… wait, as if coverage will find them. It won't. <strong>You have to reach out — pitch journalists, offer them the story, and hand them your ready-made materials</strong> — and your EPK is what makes those pitches land, because it removes the work and signals professionalism. The good news is that having a strong EPK dramatically raises your odds when you do reach out: a journalist who gets a thoughtful pitch <em>plus</em> a complete, easy-to-use press kit is far more likely to say yes than one who gets a vague email and has to chase you for everything. So this closing chapter is about the outreach — targeting the right people, giving them a reason to care, and converting your kit into coverage.</p>

<h2>Turning your EPK into coverage</h2>

<p>How to actually land press:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Target the right outlets.</b> Pitch journalists and publications that cover films like yours — your genre, your region, your niche. A tailored pitch to a relevant outlet beats a mass blast to everyone every time.</li>
  <li><b>Personalize the pitch.</b> A short, personal email that shows you know their work and explains why <em>your film</em> fits <em>their</em> audience. Generic spam gets ignored; a genuine, specific pitch gets read.</li>
  <li><b>Lead with the hook and the link.</b> Open with your news or angle (the premiere, the story behind it), then give them the EPK link so everything they need is one click away. Make saying yes effortless.</li>
  <li><b>Time it to a hook.</b> Pitch around a real moment — festival selection, release date, an award. Press cover things that are happening now; give them a timely reason.</li>
  <li><b>Offer more.</b> Make yourself available for interviews, offer exclusive stills or a clip, be responsive and easy to work with. Access and ease are what turn interest into a published piece.</li>
  <li><b>Follow up gracefully.</b> One polite follow-up is fine; pestering isn't. Be professional and warm — relationships with press pay off across your whole career, not just this film.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The whole course, in one idea — and the finish line</h2>

<p>Step back and look at what you've built. You now understand what an EPK is and why it's non-negotiable; you can distinguish the kit from the press release; you know every element that goes inside and the discipline of keeping it complete and current; you learned to gather the hard-to-get assets during production; you can write a logline, synopsis, and director's statement that make people care, assemble accurate bios and credits, curate press stills and a strong poster, and write a news-ready press release; you can lay it all out as a polished PDF and a shareable digital press page; and you know how to deploy it for festivals and for press outreach. That is the complete craft of the film EPK, and it rests on one idea that's run through every chapter: <strong>you make it easy — and professional — for the people who can help your film to help it.</strong> A busy programmer, an overloaded journalist, a skeptical buyer — each of them will do more for a film whose materials are complete, polished, easy to use, and current, and less for one whose aren't, almost regardless of the film itself. Your EPK is how you tip that in your favor. So don't let it sit finished-but-unused. Build it, keep it current, and then <em>use it</em>: reach out, pitch, offer, follow up, and put your film in front of the people who can amplify it. The films that get seen are rarely just the best films; they're the films whose makers did the unglamorous work of packaging and pitching them well. You've now got the tool and the know-how to be one of those filmmakers. Go get your film covered — congratulations on finishing the course.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A perfect EPK on your hard drive does nothing. The whole craft comes down to one idea: make it easy and professional for the people who can help your film to help it — then actually reach out and use the kit.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I once had a polished EPK and assumed press would somehow find my film. Silence. Nothing happens until you reach out. So I started pitching: I found journalists who covered my kind of film, sent each a short, personal email explaining why it fit their readers, led with the hook, and dropped in the press-page link so everything was one click away. Coverage started coming — not because the film changed, but because I made it easy and gave them a reason. The EPK is the ammunition; the pitch is pulling the trigger. Build the kit, keep it fresh, and then do the unglamorous work of putting it in front of people. That's how films get seen.</p>
</div>`,
